          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that combination of symptoms you're describing — poor sleep, lost appetite, dread before runs, and an elevated resting HR — that's your body sending a pretty clear signal, and I want to make sure we take it seriously together.\n\nWhat you're experiencing lines up with what exercise physiologists call functional overreaching, and potentially early overtraining syndrome. The elevated resting HR alone is one of the most reliable objective markers we have. I want to be straightforward with you about that, because I think you deserve a clear picture.\n\nHere's the thing about the \"I can't afford time off\" feeling — I understand it completely, and I want to gently offer a different frame: **pushing through these specific symptoms doesn't just risk a bad week. It risks the next 10 weeks.** A body in this state doesn't absorb training — it breaks down from it. Every hard session you do right now is likely making you slower, not faster.\n\nThe good news, and I mean this genuinely: **10 weeks is actually enough time** — but only if we protect the next 1-2 weeks so your body can get back to actually responding to training.\n\nHere's what I'd suggest we consider for this week:\n\n- **Drop volume by 30-40%** — not as punishment, but as an investment in weeks 3 through 10\n- **Keep everything easy pace** (5:52–6:43/km) — no quality work until your resting HR settles back down\n- **Treat sleep as the primary training stimulus right now** — genuinely, it's doing more for your fitness than any run would\n\nBefore we adjust the plan, I'd also encourage you to check in with your GP or a sports medicine doctor, especially given the appetite changes alongside everything else. That's outside my lane, and I want you to have a professional set of eyes on this.\n\nWhat feels most doable to you this week — would you rather keep the same number of runs but shorten them, or reduce the number of days and protect full rest days?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01KCezUdYJFowJngqTosuFQS"
    }
